<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="268">
Etymology L 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181719" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole astur Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole astur Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astur">astur</taxonomicName>
, hawk.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="268">
diagnosis A member of a complex of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24885" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole Westwood" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole Westwood" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pheidole</taxonomicName>
species with giant majors covered by short, bristly hair, in the larger 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33735" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole fallax Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole fallax Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fallax">fallax</taxonomicName>
group, comprising 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181719" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole astur Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole astur Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astur">astur</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33914" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole oxyops Forel" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole oxyops Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oxyops">oxyops</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33939" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole praeusta Roger" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole praeusta Roger" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="praeusta">praeusta</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181830" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole trageri Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole trageri Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trageri">trageri</taxonomicName>
. P. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181719" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole astur Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole astur Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astur">astur</taxonomicName>
is distinguished among them by the following combination of traits. Major: a patch of rugoreticulum present laterad to each antennal fossa; longitudinal carinulae immediately next to the dorsal midline of head reaches the occipital border, but the occipital lobes are smooth and shiny; postpetiolar node seen from above elliptical in shape, with subangular lateral margins; small subpostpetiolar process present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="268">Minor: occiput narrowed to form a distinct neck, followed by a broad nuchal collar; pronotum entirely smooth and shiny. Measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 2.34, HL 2.66, SL 1.20, EL 0.30, PW 1.10. Paratype minor: HW 0.68, HL 1.04, SL 1.42, EL 0.20, PW 0.50.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="268">Color Major: body and mandibles reddish brown, legs and antennae a lighter shade of reddish brown. Minor: concolorous yellow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="268">
Range I have examined material of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181719" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole astur Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole astur Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astur">astur</taxonomicName>
from French Guiana, Suriname, and Colombia, as well as Amazonian Ecuador, Peru, and Bolivia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="268">biology This large species occurs in lowland rainforest over a wide part of South America. At Cuzco Amazonico, near Puerto Maldonado, Peru, Stefan Cover (unpublished collection notes) reports colonies nesting in soil, and minors foraging on the surface of soil and leaf litter.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
